\f2 Sir James Chadwick (1891-1974) died. He\'92s famously renowned for being the English physicists discoverer of the Neutron, for which
\f3\fs32 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1935/chadwick.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 received}} the Nobel Prize for Physics (1935). He {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://search.biography.com/print_record.pl?id=7987"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 studied}} at Cambridge, and in Berlin under Geiger, then worked at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/6/6_16.htm#LaboratoryCavendish"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Cavendish Laboratory}} with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/8/8_30.htm#RutherfordErnest"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Rutherford}}, where he investigated the structure of the atom. He worked on the scattering of alpha particles and on nuclear disintegration. By bombarding beryllium with alpha particles, Chadwick {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://leifi.physik.uni-muenchen.de/web_ph12/originalarbeiten/chadwick/chadwick_neutr.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 discovered}} the neutron - a neutral particle in the atom's nucleus - for which he received the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1935. In 1932, Chadwick coined the name \'93neutron,\'94 which he {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/2/2_07.htm#Neutron"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 described}} in an article in the journal 
\f4\i Nature. 
\f3\i0 He led the UK's work on the atomic bomb in WW II, and was knighted in 1945.
\f1\fs24 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\

